twentieth century: social problems have been analyzed as if they had no economic dimension and economic problems as if they had no social dimension. Today, however, there is a dialogue between the two fields, as economists take on social topics and as sociologists become interested in rational choice and "new economic sociology." The interviewees describe how they came to challenge the present separation between economics and sociology, what they think of the various proposals to integrate the fields, and how they envision the future. The author summarizes the results of the conversations in the final chapter. The individual interviews also serve as superb introductions to the work of these scholars.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / General.2bisacsh  a.  aAkerlof, George A.  aArrow, Kenneth J.  aBecker, Gary S.  aBell, Daniel.  aBoulding, Kenneth.  aColeman, James S.  aCyert, Richard M.  aDewey, John.  aDurkheim, Emile.  aElster, Jon.  aFriedman, Milton.  aGranovetter, Mark.  aHechter, Michael.  aHirschman, Albert O.  aInsull, Samuel.  aKahneman, Daniel.  aKeynes, John Maynard.  aLandes, David S.  aLeontief, Wassily.  aMarch, James G.  aMarx, Karl.  aOlson, Mancur.  aParsons, Talcott.  aRaiffa, Howard.  aSamuelson, Paul A.  aSchumpeter, Joseph A.  aSimon, Herbert.  aStinchcombe, Arthur L.  aTullock, Gordon.  aVickrey, William.  aWeber, Max.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691221328zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691221328423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691221328.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package A